{"title_page": "Allen Daviau", "text_new": "{{short description|American cinematographer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Allen Daviau, [[American Society of Cinematographers|A.S.C.]]\n| image       = Deyellspielbergdaviau.jpg\n| caption     = Peter R.J. Deyell, [[Steven Spielberg]], and Allen Daviau\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1942|06|14}}\n| birth_place = [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|04|15|1942|06|14}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation  = [[Cinematographer]]\n| yearsactive = 1967&ndash;2010\n| partner     = \n| baftaawards = \n}}\n\n'''Allen Daviau''', [[American Society of Cinematographers|A.S.C.]] (June 14, 1942 &ndash; April 15, 2020) was an American [[cinematographer]].  He was known for his collaborations with [[Steven Spielberg]] as a cinematography for his work on, ''[[E.T. the Extra Terrestrial]]'' (1982), ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]'' (1985), and ''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]'' (1987). He was nominated and won numerous awards, including 5 [[Academy Award]] nominations and 2 [[British Academy Film Award]] nominations, with one win. In addition to his work in film, Daviau served as Cinematographer-in-Residence at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ucla-taps-bailey-kodak-cinematographer-residence-16261/|title=UCLA Taps Bailey as Kodak Cinematographer-in-Residence|date=April 13, 2010}}</ref> He died on April 15, 2020, at the age of 77 as a result of complications from [[COVID-19]] at the [[Motion Picture & Television Country House and Hospital]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/allen-daviau-dead-spielberg-cinematographer-five-time-oscar-nominee-was-77-1290572|title=Allen Daviau, Spielberg Cinematographer and Five-Time Oscar Nominee, Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 77|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBorn on June 14, 1942, in New Orleans and raised in Los Angeles, Daviau was introduced to Spielberg in the late 1960s. \"Steven had seen some of my [[16mm]] work,\u201d he said in a 2007 interview. \"He and I shared a great love of movies.\"<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nDaviau's career jumpstarted when he was introduced to an aspiring filmmaker, [[Steven Spielberg]] in 1967 where they worked on two early short films. They continued their professional working career by collaborating on ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982); \"Kick the Can,\" a segment from ''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]'' (1983), ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' (1984), ''[[The Color Purple (1985 film)|The Color Purple]]'' (1985), and an episode of the [[NBC]] anthology series ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' titled, \"Ghost Train\" (1985), ''[[Empire of the Sun]]'' (1987).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nDaviau's work also includes [[John Schlesinger]]'s ''[[The Falcon and the Snowman]]'' (1985), the Spielberg-produced ''[[Harry and the Hendersons]]'' (1987), [[Albert Brooks]]' ''[[Defending Your Life]]'' (1991), [[Barry Levinson]]'s ''[[Avalon (1990 film)|Avalon]]'' (1990) and ''[[Bugsy]]'' (1991), [[Peter Weir]]'s ''[[Fearless (1993 film)|Fearless]]'' (1993), [[Frank Marshall]]'s ''[[Congo (film)|Congo]]'' (1995), [[Rand Ravich]]'s ''[[The Astronaut's Wife]]'' (1999) and [[Stephen Sommers]]' ''[[Van Helsing]]'' (2004), his final feature.\n\nHe received lifetime achievement awards from the [[Art Directors Guild]] in 1997 and the [[American Society of Cinematographers]] in 2007.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/allen-daviau-dead-dies-e-t-empire-of-the-sun-1234582518/|title= \u2018E.T.\u2019 Cinematographer Allen Daviau Dies of COVID-19 at 77|website= Variety|accessdate= April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his career, Daviau shot thousands of commercials, documentaries, industrials and educational films, and created psychedelic special-effects lighting for [[Roger Corman]]'s ''[[The Trip (1967 film)|The Trip]]'' (1967), before he gained entry into the International Photographers Guild.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial''===\nWhile doing a lawnmower commercial in [[Arizona]], he learned that Spielberg was looking for a cinematographer for ''E.T.'' and sent the director a tape of a 1980 [[CBS]] telefilm that he shot, ''The Boy Who Drank Too Much'', starring [[Scott Baio]]. \"It had a lot of mood, and it's about kids, so I knew Steven would watch it!\" Daviau said. Spielberg stated, he  contacted Daviau for his next feature saying, \"I did something I rarely do. I didn't think twice; I picked up the phone and asked Allen if he would photograph my next feature.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theasc.com/ac_magazine/January2007/AllenDaviauASC/page1.html|title= Allen Davaiu, ASC one of cinematography\u2019s most ethusiastic and accomplished ambassadors, reflects on his career after earning the Lifetime Achievement Award|website= theasc.com|accessdate= April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nDaviau died on April 15, 2020, at the age of 77 as a result of complications from [[COVID-19]] at the [[Motion Picture & Television Country House and Hospital]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nWhen news reached Spielberg recently that Daviau was ill, the famed filmmaker sent a letter to him that recounted their years of friendship and collaboration together. It was read to Daviau several times at his bedside just before he died, the MPTF said. Said Spielberg: \"Allen and I started our careers side by side \u2026 [he] was a wonderful artist, but his warmth and humanity were as powerful as his lens. He was a singular talent and a beautiful human being.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwmt.com/news/entertainment/et-bugsy-cinematographer-allen-daviau-dies-at-77|title= 'E.T.,' 'Bugsy' cinematographer Allen Daviau dies at 77|website= Wwmt.com|accessdate= April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''\n|[[Steven Spielberg]]\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]''\n|Steven Spielberg<br>[[Joe Dante]]\n|Segments \"[[Kick the Can]]\" and \"[[It's a Good Life (The Twilight Zone)|It's a Good Life]]\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1985\n|''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]''\n|Steven Spielberg\n|Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[The Falcon and the Snowman]]''\n|[[John Schlesinger]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1987\n|''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]''\n|Steven Spielberg\n|[[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]<br>[[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry and the Hendersons]]''\n|[[William Dear]]\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Avalon (1990 film)|Avalon]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[Barry Levinson]]\n|Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1991\n|''[[Bugsy]]''\n|[[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[Defending Your Life]]''\n|[[Albert Brooks]]\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Fearless (1993 film)|Fearless]]''\n|[[Peter Weir]]\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Congo (film)|Congo]]''\n|[[Frank Marshall (producer)|Frank Marshall]]\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[The Astronaut's Wife]]''\n|[[Rand Ravich]]\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Tigger Movie]]''\n|[[Jun Falkenstein]]\n|Animated feature\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Van Helsing (film)|Van Helsing]]''\n|[[Stephen Sommers]]\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|1974 || ''Mooch'' || Television Movie \n|-\n|1979 || ''The Streets of L.A.'' || Television Movie\n|-\n|1980 || ''[[The Boy Who Drank Too Much]]'' || Television Movie \n|-\n|1980 || ''Rage! || Television Movie\n|-\n|1982 || ''[[McDonaldland]]'' || Episode: Skating \n|-\n|1983 || ''Legs'' || Television Movie\n|-\n|1985 || ''[[Amazing Stories (1985 TV series)|Amazing Stories]]'' || Episode: Ghost Train \n|-\n|1996 || ''International Cinematographer's <br/> Guild Heritage Series'' || Episode: Vittorio Storaro \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0005679|Allen Daviau}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Allen Daviau\n| list =\n{{American Society of Cinematographers Theatrical Release Award}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography 1985\u20132009}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daviau, Allen}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design people]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in California]]\n\n{{US-cinematographer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American cinematographer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Allen Daviau, [[American Society of Cinematographers|A.S.C.]]\n| image       = Deyellspielbergdaviau.jpg\n| caption     = Peter R.J. Deyell, [[Steven Spielberg]], and Allen Daviau\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1942|06|14}}\n| birth_place = [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|04|15|1942|06|14}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation  = [[Cinematographer]]\n| yearsactive = 1967&ndash;2010\n| partner     = \n| baftaawards = \n}}\n\n'''Allen Daviau''', [[American Society of Cinematographers|A.S.C.]] (June 14, 1942 &ndash; April 15, 2020) was an American [[cinematographer]].  He was known for his collaborations with [[Steven Spielberg]] as a cinematography for his work on, ''[[E.T. the Extra Terrestrial]]'' (1982), ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]'' (1985), and ''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]'' (1987). He was nominated and won numerous awards, including 5 [[Academy Award]] nominations and 2 [[British Academy Film Award]] nominations, with one win. In addition to his work in film, Daviau served as Cinematographer-in-Residence at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ucla-taps-bailey-kodak-cinematographer-residence-16261/|title=UCLA Taps Bailey as Kodak Cinematographer-in-Residence|date=April 13, 2010}}</ref> He died on April 15, 2020, at the age of 77 as a result of complications from [[COVID-19]] at the [[Motion Picture & Television Country House and Hospital]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/allen-daviau-dead-spielberg-cinematographer-five-time-oscar-nominee-was-77-1290572|title=Allen Daviau, Spielberg Cinematographer and Five-Time Oscar Nominee, Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 77|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBorn on June 14, 1942, in New Orleans and raised in Los Angeles, Daviau was introduced to Spielberg in the late 1960s. \"Steven had seen some of my [[16mm]] work,\u201d he said in a 2007 interview. \"He and I shared a great love of movies.\"<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nDaviau's career jumpstarted when he was introduced to an aspiring filmmaker, [[Steven Spielberg]] in 1967 where they worked on two early short films. They continued their professional working career by collaborating on ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982); \"Kick the Can,\" a segment from ''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]'' (1983), ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' (1984), ''[[The Color Purple (1985 film)|The Color Purple]]'' (1985), and an episode of the [[NBC]] anthology series ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' titled, \"Ghost Train\" (1985), ''[[Empire of the Sun]]'' (1987).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nDaviau's work also includes [[John Schlesinger]]'s ''[[The Falcon and the Snowman]]'' (1985), the Spielberg-produced ''[[Harry and the Hendersons]]'' (1987), [[Albert Brooks]]' ''[[Defending Your Life]]'' (1991), [[Barry Levinson]]'s ''[[Avalon (1990 film)|Avalon]]'' (1990) and ''[[Bugsy]]'' (1991), [[Peter Weir]]'s ''[[Fearless (1993 film)|Fearless]]'' (1993), [[Frank Marshall]]'s ''[[Congo (film)|Congo]]'' (1995), [[Rand Ravich]]'s ''[[The Astronaut's Wife]]'' (1999) and [[Stephen Sommers]]' ''[[Van Helsing]]'' (2004), his final feature.\n\nHe received lifetime achievement awards from the [[Art Directors Guild]] in 1997 and the [[American Society of Cinematographers]] in 2007.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/allen-daviau-dead-dies-e-t-empire-of-the-sun-1234582518/|title= \u2018E.T.\u2019 Cinematographer Allen Daviau Dies of COVID-19 at 77|website= Variety|accessdate= April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his career, Daviau shot thousands of commercials, documentaries, industrials and educational films, and created psychedelic special-effects lighting for [[Roger Corman]]'s ''[[The Trip (1967 film)|The Trip]]'' (1967), before he gained entry into the International Photographers Guild.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial''===\nWhile doing a lawnmower commercial in [[Arizona]], he learned that Spielberg was looking for a cinematographer for ''E.T.'' and sent the director a tape of a 1980 [[CBS]] telefilm that he shot, ''The Boy Who Drank Too Much'', starring [[Scott Baio]]. \"It had a lot of mood, and it's about kids, so I knew Steven would watch it!\" Daviau said. Spielberg stated, he  contacted Daviau for his next feature saying, \"I did something I rarely do. I didn't think twice; I picked up the phone and asked Allen if he would photograph my next feature.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theasc.com/ac_magazine/January2007/AllenDaviauASC/page1.html|title= Allen Davaiu, ASC one of cinematography\u2019s most ethusiastic and accomplished ambassadors, reflects on his career after earning the Lifetime Achievement Award|website= theasc.com|accessdate= April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nDaviau died on April 15, 2020, at the age of 77 as a result of complications from [[COVID-19]] at the [[Motion Picture & Television Country House and Hospital]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\nWhen news reached Spielberg recently that Daviau was ill, the famed filmaker sent a letter to him that recounted their years of friendship and collaboration together. It was read to Daviau several times at his bedside just before he died, the MPTF said. Said Spielberg: \"Allen and I started our careers side by side \u2026 [he] was a wonderful artist, but his warmth and humanity were as powerful as his lens. He was a singular talent and a beautiful human being.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwmt.com/news/entertainment/et-bugsy-cinematographer-allen-daviau-dies-at-77|title= 'E.T.,' 'Bugsy' cinematographer Allen Daviau dies at 77|website= Wwmt.com|accessdate= April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''\n|[[Steven Spielberg]]\n|[[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]''\n|Steven Spielberg<br>[[Joe Dante]]\n|Segments \"[[Kick the Can]]\" and \"[[It's a Good Life (The Twilight Zone)|It's a Good Life]]\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1985\n|''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]''\n|Steven Spielberg\n|Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[The Falcon and the Snowman]]''\n|[[John Schlesinger]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1987\n|''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]''\n|Steven Spielberg\n|[[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]<br>[[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[Harry and the Hendersons]]''\n|[[William Dear]]\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Avalon (1990 film)|Avalon]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[Barry Levinson]]\n|Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1991\n|''[[Bugsy]]''\n|[[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography]]<br>Nominated \u2013 [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography]]\n|-\n|''[[Defending Your Life]]''\n|[[Albert Brooks]]\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Fearless (1993 film)|Fearless]]''\n|[[Peter Weir]]\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Congo (film)|Congo]]''\n|[[Frank Marshall (producer)|Frank Marshall]]\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[The Astronaut's Wife]]''\n|[[Rand Ravich]]\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Tigger Movie]]''\n|[[Jun Falkenstein]]\n|Animated feature\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Van Helsing (film)|Van Helsing]]''\n|[[Stephen Sommers]]\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|1974 || ''Mooch'' || Television Movie \n|-\n|1979 || ''The Streets of L.A.'' || Television Movie\n|-\n|1980 || ''[[The Boy Who Drank Too Much]]'' || Television Movie \n|-\n|1980 || ''Rage! || Television Movie\n|-\n|1982 || ''[[McDonaldland]]'' || Episode: Skating \n|-\n|1983 || ''Legs'' || Television Movie\n|-\n|1985 || ''[[Amazing Stories (1985 TV series)|Amazing Stories]]'' || Episode: Ghost Train \n|-\n|1996 || ''International Cinematographer's <br/> Guild Heritage Series'' || Episode: Vittorio Storaro \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0005679|Allen Daviau}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Allen Daviau\n| list =\n{{American Society of Cinematographers Theatrical Release Award}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography 1985\u20132009}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daviau, Allen}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design people]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in California]]\n\n{{US-cinematographer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAWylie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:sp.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Daviau"}
{"title_page": "Poecilotheria rufilata", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Red slate ornamental tarantula\n| taxon = Poecilotheria rufilata\n| image = Poecilotheria rufilata 8LA2.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| status = EN \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN/>\n| authority = Pocock, 1899<ref name=WSC_s37829/>\n| range_map = \n}}\n\n'''''Poecilotheria rufilata''''', also known as the '''red slate ornamental''', '''reddish parachute spider''', '''Travancore slate-red''', or '''rufus parachute spider''', is an arboreal tarantula. It is endemic to South [[Western Ghats]] of [[India]]. It is classed as \"endangered\", threatened by habitat loss and smuggling for the pet trade.<ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/63567/0 |title=''Poecilotheria rufilata'' |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikebasictarantula.com/Poe-rufilata-care-sheet.html |title=''P. rufilata'' |publisher=My Basic Tarantula |accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe female is larger than the male, with a body length of about 8&nbsp;cm, the male being at most 3.5&nbsp;cm in body length.<ref name=Schm03>{{Cite book |last1=Schmidt |first1=G. |date=2003 |title=Die Vogelspinnen: Eine weltweite \u00dcbersicht |publication-place=Hohenwarsleben |publisher=Westarp Wissenschaften |isbn=978-3-89432-899-3 |series=Neue Brehm-B\u00fccherei |page=246 }}</ref> In measured wild-caught specimens, the longest leg of the female was up to 8&nbsp;cm in total length, that of the male up to 7&nbsp;cm.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Charpentier |first=P. |date=1996 |title=The illustrated redescription of: ''Poecilotheria rufilata'' Pocock 1899 |journal=Exothermae Magazine |pages=14\u201324 }}</ref>\n\nIn the first and fourth pairs of legs, the ground color is yellow. The femur is also yellow proximally, ending with a black part and a thin yellow band. The tibia is yellow.<ref name=poecilotheria>{{cite book|author=Nanayakkara, Ranil P.|year=2014|title= Tiger Spiders ''Poecilotheria'' of Sri Lanka |publisher=Biodiversity Secretariat, Ministry of Environmental & Renewable Energy |location= Colombo |pages= 167|isbn= 978-955-0033-58-4}}</ref>\n[[File:Poecilotheria rufilata.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Ecology==\nThe species is confined to the south [[Western Ghats]] of India, where it lives in tree hollows, under tree bark, and in rock crevices. It sometimes enters human settlements. It is classed as \"endangered\", with the major threats being habitat degradation and collection for the pet trade. It is smuggled out of India for sale in Europe and America.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==As a pet==\nCompared to other tiger spiders, this species is much more docile, but in extreme disturbances, will bite. However, spiderlings are known to be much stronger jumpers and strike faster than adults.<ref name=\"fearnottarantulas\">{{cite web | url=https://fearnottarantulas.com/poecilotheria-rufilata-red-slate-ornamental-2/ | title=''Poecilotheria rufilata'' (Red Slate Ornamental) | accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tarantula.all-infos.eu/e_v_p_rufilata.htm | title=General information of P. rufilata | publisher=Tarantula | accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=WSC_s37829>{{cite web |title=Taxon details ''Poecilotheria rufilata'' Pocock, 1899 |work=World Spider Catalog |publisher=Natural History Museum Bern |url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/species/37829 |accessdate=29 February 2016 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160312082300/http://www.arkive.org/reddish-parachute-spider/poecilotheria-rufilata/ Photos]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4128588}}\n\n[[Category:Poecilotheria|rufilata]]\n[[Category:Spiders of India]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of India]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1899]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Red slate ornamental tarantula\n| taxon = Poecilotheria rufilata\n| image = Poecilotheria rufilata 8LA2.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| status = EN \n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN/>\n| authority = Pocock, 1899<ref name=WSC_s37829/>\n| range_map = \n}}\n\n'''''Poecilotheria rufilata''''', also known as the '''red slate ornamental''', '''reddish parachute spider''', '''Travancore slate-red''' or '''rufus parachute spider''', is an arboreal tarantula. It is endemic to South [[Western Ghats]] of [[India]]. It is classed as \"endangered\", threatened by habitat loss and smuggling for the pet trade.<ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/63567/0 |title=''Poecilotheria rufilata'' |accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mikebasictarantula.com/Poe-rufilata-care-sheet.html |title=''P. rufilata'' |publisher=My Basic Tarantula |accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe female is larger than the male, with a body length of about 8&nbsp;cm, the male being at most 3.5&nbsp;cm in body length.<ref name=Schm03>{{Cite book |last1=Schmidt |first1=G. |date=2003 |title=Die Vogelspinnen: Eine weltweite \u00dcbersicht |publication-place=Hohenwarsleben |publisher=Westarp Wissenschaften |isbn=978-3-89432-899-3 |series=Neue Brehm-B\u00fccherei |page=246 }}</ref> In measured wild-caught specimens, the longest leg of the female was up to 8&nbsp;cm in total length, that of the male up to 7&nbsp;cm.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Charpentier |first=P. |date=1996 |title=The illustrated redescription of: ''Poecilotheria rufilata'' Pocock 1899 |journal=Exothermae Magazine |pages=14\u201324 }}</ref>\n\nIn the first and fourth pairs of legs, the ground color is yellow. The femur is also yellow proximally, ending with a black part and a thin yellow band. The tibia is yellow.<ref name=poecilotheria>{{cite book|author=Nanayakkara, Ranil P.|year=2014|title= Tiger Spiders ''Poecilotheria'' of Sri Lanka |publisher=Biodiversity Secretariat, Ministry of Environmental & Renewable Energy |location= Colombo |pages= 167|isbn= 978-955-0033-58-4}}</ref>\n[[File:Poecilotheria rufilata.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Ecology==\nThe species is confined to the south [[Western Ghats]] of India, where it lives in tree hollows, under tree bark, and in rock crevices. It sometimes enters human settlements. It is classed as \"endangered\", with the major threats being habitat degradation and collection for the pet trade. It is smuggled out of India for sale in Europe and America.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\n==As a pet==\nCompared to other tiger spiders, this species is much more docile, but in extreme disturbances, will bite. However, spiderlings are known to be much stronger jumpers and strike faster than adults.<ref name=\"fearnottarantulas\">{{cite web | url=https://fearnottarantulas.com/poecilotheria-rufilata-red-slate-ornamental-2/ | title=''Poecilotheria rufilata'' (Red Slate Ornamental) | accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tarantula.all-infos.eu/e_v_p_rufilata.htm | title=General information of P. rufilata | publisher=Tarantula | accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=WSC_s37829>{{cite web |title=Taxon details ''Poecilotheria rufilata'' Pocock, 1899 |work=World Spider Catalog |publisher=Natural History Museum Bern |url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/species/37829 |accessdate=29 February 2016 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160312082300/http://www.arkive.org/reddish-parachute-spider/poecilotheria-rufilata/ Photos]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4128588}}\n\n[[Category:Poecilotheria|rufilata]]\n[[Category:Spiders of India]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of India]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1899]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poecilotheria_rufilata"}
{"title_page": "Bradley Steven Perry", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bradley Steven Perry\n| image = Bradley Steven Perry 2011.jpg\n| caption = Perry in July 2011\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1998|11|23}}<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\" />\n| birth_place = <!-- Do not add a location without a reliable independent secondary source. -->\n| nationality = <!-- Only if different from birth place -->\n| occupation = Actor\n| residence = [[Southern California]]\n| years_active = 2007\u2013present\n| known for = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]''\n* ''[[Mighty Med]]''\n* ''[[Pants on Fire (film)|Pants on Fire]]''\n* ''[[Lab Rats: Elite Force]]''\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Bradley Steven Perry''' (born November 23, 1998<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/bradley-steven-perry-58764201/ |title=Bradley Steven Perry |website=Hollywood.com |accessdate=June 17, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813142600/http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/bradley-steven-perry-58764201/|archivedate=August 13, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>) is an American actor. He is known for his role as [[Good Luck Charlie#Gabe Duncan|Gabe Duncan]] on the [[Disney Channel]] family sitcom ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'',<ref name=\"V-GLC\">{{Cite journal |last = Lowry|first = Brian |url = https://variety.com/2010/scene/markets-festivals/good-luck-charlie-1117942513/ |title = Review: \u2018Good Luck Charlie\u2019 |date = March 31, 2010 |work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date = September 12, 2015}}</ref> and for his role as Roger Elliston III in Disney's ''[[High School Musical (film series)|High School Musical]]'' spin-off film ''[[Sharpay's Fabulous Adventure]]''. Following this, Perry co-starred on the [[Disney XD]] comedies ''[[Mighty Med]]''<ref name=\"THR-MM\">{{Cite news |last = Ng|first = Philiana |url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-xd-sets-debut-mighty-623331 |title = Disney XD Sets Debut for 'Mighty Med' Comedy Series (Exclusive) |date = September 9, 2013 |work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date = September 12, 2015}}</ref> and its spinoff ''[[Lab Rats: Elite Force]]'', where he played the role of Kaz.\n\n==Career==\nIn 2008, Perry began his professional acting career at the age of 10 with small roles in the films ''Choose Connor'', and ''Magnificent Max''.<ref name=\"CharleyRossman.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.charleyrossman.com/video2.html|title='Magnificent Max' Short Film and Stunts|accessdate=August 30, 2011|work=CharleyRossman.com}}</ref>  The following year, he made his television debut with a guest-starring role on the [[CBS]] crime-drama ''[[Without a Trace]]''.<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900044&type=perry|title=Bradley Steven Perry \"Gabe Duncan\"|accessdate=August 16, 2012|work=DisneyChannelMedianet|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029190413/http://www.disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900044&type=perry|archivedate=October 29, 2013}}</ref>  Over the next year, Perry continued to appear in small comedic roles in such films as  ''[[The Goods: Live Hard, Sell Hard]]'', ''[[Opposite Day (film)|Opposite Day]]'', and ''[[Old Dogs (film)|Old Dogs]]''.<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\"/>\n\nIn 2010, Perry starred on the [[Disney Channel]] family sitcom ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]''.  On the series, Perry played the mischievous and scheming Gabe Duncan, the third of five siblings in the Duncan family. In 2011, he starred in the movie ''[[Good Luck Charlie, It's Christmas!]]''<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\"/><ref name=\"MSN.com\">{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.msn.com/beacon/editorial10_poll.aspx?ptid=20b5ea82-a80a-439b-9f83-80beef748e49&silentchk=1|title=Meet 'Good Luck Charlie' Star Bradley Steven Perry|accessdate=August 24, 2011|work=MSN.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319035503/http://entertainment.msn.com/beacon/editorial10_poll.aspx?ptid=20b5ea82-a80a-439b-9f83-80beef748e49&silentchk=1|archivedate=March 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"TimeForKids.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.timeforkids.com/TFK/kids/news/story/0,28277,2052636,00.html |title=Bradley Steven Perry: Just His Luck |work=[[Time for Kids]] |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227213656/http://www.timeforkids.com/TFK/kids/news/story/0%2C28277%2C2052636%2C00.html |archivedate=February 27, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"GirlsLife.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.girlslife.com/post/2010/04/01/bradley-steven-perry.aspx?cp=2|title=Hangin' with Good Luck Charlie's Bradley Steven Perry|work=[[Girls' Life (magazine)|Girls' Life]]|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the same year, Perry co-starred in the Disney Channel original movie  ''[[Sharpay's Fabulous Adventure]]''.  In the film, Perry played Roger Elliston III, a precocious young dog owner and Sharpay's rival, competing to get his dog a starring role on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\" /><ref name=\"MSN.com\" /><ref name=\"TimeForKids.com\" /> In 2013, Perry began playing Kaz on the [[Disney XD]] show ''[[Mighty Med]]'' alongside [[Jake Short]] and [[Paris Berelc]].<ref name=\"THR-MM\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disneyxdmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=3156446&type=Main |publisher=Disney XD Medianet |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422232928/http://www.disneyxdmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=3156446&type=Main |url-status=dead |archivedate=April 22, 2014 |title=Mighty Med |year=2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Perry starred as Jack Parker in the [[List of programs broadcast by Disney XD|Disney XD Original Movie]] ''[[Pants on Fire (film)|Pants on Fire]]'', which premiered on [[Disney XD]] on November 9, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thewrap.com/disney-xd-movie-pants-on-fire-set-for-november-premiere/|title=Disney XD Movie 'Pants on Fire' Set for November Premiere|date=2014-10-09|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-24}}</ref> In 2015, ''Mighty Med'' ended its run, but Perry continued to play Kaz on the [[Spin-off (media)|spinoff]] series ''[[Lab Rats: Elite Force]]'', which premiered in March 2016.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/disney-xd-lab-rats-elite-force-spinoff-mighty-med-1201585323/ |title=Disney XD Greenlights \u2018Lab Rats\u2019 and \u2018Mighty Med\u2019 Spinoff Series |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 3, 2015 |accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/09/lab-rats-mighty-med-end-spinoff-series-disney-xd-1201513610/|title=Lab Rats & Mighty Med Spin-off Series to Succeed the Two Comedies on Disney XD|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=September 3, 2015|accessdate=September 3, 2015}}</ref>\nIn 2017, he appeared in ''[[Descendants: Wicked World]]'' as Zevon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/07/13/descendants-wicked-world-season-2-renewed-new-cast-characters/|title=Descendants: Wicked World Renewed for Season 2, Taps Disney Channel Star to Voice Son of Emperor's Yzma|last=Swift|first=Andy|last2=Swift|first2=Andy|date=2016-07-13|website=TVLine|access-date=2017-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPerry lives in [[Southern California]] with his parents and three older sisters.<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\"/><ref name=\"MSN.com\"/><ref name=\"TimeForKids.com\"/><ref name=\"GirlsLife.com\"/> He currently attends the [[University of Southern California]] and will graduate with the class of 2021. He was homeschooled on the set of ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'' and plays on a local baseball team in his free time.<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\"/><ref name=\"MSN.com\"/>  Perry is also an avid fan of the [[Boston Red Sox]] and the [[New England Patriots]] and appeared in an [[NBC Sunday Night Football]] television promo as \"The Patriots Kid\".<ref name=\"DisneyChannelMedianet\"/><ref name=\"FanLaLa.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CL7XIXD9vBo|title=Bradley Steven Perry's Dressing Room|accessdate=August 24, 2011|work=FanLaLa.com}}</ref>\n\nPerry contributes to various charitable causes including Mattel Children's Hospital, which provides treatment for children suffering from pediatric diseases; [[Toys for Tots]], which donates toys to underprivileged children during [[Christmas]]; and the Make-a-Wish Foundation, which secures wishes to children with life-threatening medical conditions.<ref name=\"MaximoTV.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NHiJyMpC2Oo|title=Mendler, Dolley & Perry - 2010 Hollywood Christmas Parade|accessdate=August 24, 2011|work=MaximoTV.com}}</ref><ref name=\"HollywoodTeenZine.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodteenzine.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1636&Itemid=82|title=11th Annual Party On The Pier|accessdate=August 24, 2011|work=HollywoodTeenZine.com}}</ref><ref name=\"KVEWTV.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kvewtv.com/article/2011/jul/26/prosser-girl-incurable-disorder-heads-hollywood/|title=Prosser Girl Heads to Hollywood|work=[[KVEW-TV]]|date=July 26, 2011|accessdate=August 24, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927215513/http://www.kvewtv.com/article/2011/jul/26/prosser-girl-incurable-disorder-heads-hollywood/|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film roles\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Choose Connor''\n| School Boy\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Magnificent Max''\n| Georgie Rosenthal\n| Short film<ref name=\"CharleyRossman.com\" />\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Old Dogs (film)|Old Dogs]]''\n| Soccer Kid\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Who Shot Mamba?''\n| David\n|\n|-\