n|Existing\n|}\n\n===Other Venues===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Events\n!Capacity\n!Status\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Rose Bowl, Pasadena]], CA\n|Football\n|92,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Angel Stadium]], Anaheim, CA\n|Baseball and softball\n|45,457\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lake Perris]], Moreno Valley,CA / Perris,CA\n|Canoe sprint\n|12,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Rowing\n|12,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Frank G. Bonelli Regional Park]], San Dimas, CA\n|Mountain biking\n|3,000\n|Temporary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Honda Center]], Anaheim, CA\n|Indoor volleyball\n|18,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Universal Studios Hollywood|Universal Studios]], Hollywood, CA\n|[[International Broadcast Centre|International Broadcast Center]]/MPC<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/news/universal-studios-hollywood-soundstage-theme-park-expansion-1201795566/|title=Universal to Build New Soundstage Complex, Expand Theme Park in 5-Year Plan (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Ted|last=Johnson|date=June 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827100145/http://variety.com/2016/biz/news/universal-studios-hollywood-soundstage-theme-park-expansion-1201795566/|archivedate=August 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| \u2013\n|Existing\n|-\n!\n![[Westside (Los Angeles County)|Los Angeles Westside Area]]\n!\n!\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Santa Monica State Beach]], Santa Monica, CA\n|Beach volleyball\n|12,000\n|Temporary\n|-\n|Skateboarding\n|10,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Surfing\n|8,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|3&times;3 Basketball\n| \u2013\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Riviera Country Club]], Los Angeles, CA\n|Golf\n|30,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Pauley Pavilion]] ([[UCLA]]), Westwood, CA\n|Olympic Village, Olympic Village Training Center\n| \u2013\n|Existing\n|-\n|Wrestling\n|12,500\n|Existing\n|-\n|Judo\n|12,500\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[SoFi Stadium|LA Stadium at Hollywood Park]], Inglewood, CA\n|Opening and Closing Ceremonies\n|100,000\n|Under construction\n|-\n|Football\n|100,000\n|Under construction\n|-\n|Archery \n|8,000 (Stadium Lake)\n|Under construction\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]], Inglewood, CA\n|Gymnastics\n|17,000\n|Existing\n|}\n\n====Olympic ceremonies====\nOlympic ceremonies could be held in two venues simultaneously; the ceremony would begin at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] in Exposition Park to honor the legacy of the Olympics in Los Angeles and then transfer to the new [[SoFi Stadium]] in Inglewood to proceed with the parade of athletes, oaths, traditional Olympic protocol and the lighting of a cauldron. LA 2024 bid leaders wish to use the new LA stadium to dispel negative thought about using the LA Memorial Coliseum for a third Olympics. They also cite ticket sales at both sites as extra cash flow for the committee. Additionally, the LA 2024 team stated they would reverse the closing ceremony with a start at LA Stadium and close the show at the LA Coliseum if chosen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-la2024-olympic-ceremonies-20170116-story.html|title=L.A. organizers propose linked, simultaneous Olympic ceremonies for Coliseum, Inglewood stadium|date=January 16, 2017|publisher=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116175332/http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-la2024-olympic-ceremonies-20170116-story.html|archivedate=January 16, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Football (soccer) stadia==\nFootball venues will be situated within [[Los Angeles]] and in other parts of California, to be determined.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part3_english.pdf|title=LA2024 Games Delivery, Experience and Venue Legacy|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204004759/https://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part3_english.pdf|archivedate=February 4, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nPotential venues:\n* [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]], [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] (92,542 capacity) \u2013 3 group matches, quarterfinals, semifinals and women's final\n* [[SoFi Stadium]], [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]] (80,000) \u2013 3 group matches, quarterfinals, semifinals and men's final\n* [[Levi's Stadium]], [[Santa Clara, California]] (68,500) \u2013 5 group matches, quarterfinals, and men's bronze medal match\n* [[California Memorial Stadium]], [[Berkeley, California]] (63,000) - 8 group matches\n* [[Stanford Stadium]], [[Stanford, California|Stanford]] (50,000) \u2013 5 group matches, quarterfinals and women's bronze medal match\n* New [[MLS]] Stadium, [[San Diego]] (32,000) \u2013 8 group matches\n* [[Banc of California Stadium]], [[Exposition Park, Los Angeles|Exposition Park]] (22,000) \u2013 8 group matches\n* [[Avaya Stadium]], [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] (20,000) \u2013 8 group matches\n\nAccording to LA2024.org there will be eight venues in the borders of State of California (probably eight venues in four municipalities).\n\n===Changed venues===\nPiggyback Yard, a rail yard along the [[LA River]], was the original proposed location for the Olympic Village, but the plan was abandoned due to financial concerns. Instead, UCLA became the new proposed location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://la.curbed.com/2016/1/25/10843466/los-angeles-2024-olympics-village-piggyback-yard-ucla-usc|title=Los Angeles Abandons Plans to Rehabilitate Prime LA River Site For 2024 Olympics|first=Adrian Glick|last=Kudler|date=January 25, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813093652/http://la.curbed.com/2016/1/25/10843466/los-angeles-2024-olympics-village-piggyback-yard-ucla-usc|archivedate=August 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1932 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[1984 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[Los Angeles bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160422105136/https://la24.org/ LA 2024]\n* [https://twitter.com/LA2024 LA 2024 on Twitter]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/la2024 LA 2024 on Facebook]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/LA2028Games/ LA 2024 on Instagram]\n\n===Candidature documents===\n* [http://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part1_english.pdf Stage 1: Vision, Games Concept and Strategy]\n* [http://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part2_english.pdf Stage 2: Governance, Legal and Venue Funding]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20161203123854/https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/1356850/LA2024Budget.pdf Budget released December 2, 2016]\n* [https://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part3_english.pdf Stage 3: Games Delivery, Experience and Venue Legacy]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20170514231518/http://www.alternativasostenibile.it/sites/default/files/LA2024_Sustainability%20Vision%20Booklet.pdf Sustainability Vision]\n\n=== IOC Documents ===\n* [https://www.olympic.org/host-city-election-2024 Report of the IOC Evaluation Commission 2024]\n* [https://stillmed.olympic.org/media/Document%20Library/OlympicOrg/Games/Summer-Games/2028-Los-Angeles/IOC-2028-Evaluation-Commission-report.pdf#_ga=2.62499948.1541299323.1505073861-1399196343.1497019155 Report of the IOC Evaluation Commission 2028]\n\n{{United States bids for the Olympic Games}}\n{{Bids for the 2024 and 2028 Summer Olympics}}\n\n[[Category:2024 Summer Olympics bids]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Summer Olympics bids of the United States|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{use American English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Olympic bid|2024|Summer|\n| Paralympics  = yes\n| logo = File:LA 2024 Olympic Bid Logo.svg\n| logo-size =200px\n| map =\n| fullname = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| committee = [[United States Olympic Committee]] (USOC)\n| chair = [[Casey Wasserman]]\n| score =\n| history = {{unbulleted list|[[1932 Summer Olympics]]|[[1984 Summer Olympics]]}}\n| result = {{bulleted list|[[Paris]] selected as host|Los Angeles awarded [[2028 Summer Olympics]]}}\n}}\n{{2024 Summer Olympics}}\n\nThe '''Los Angeles bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics and Summer Paralympics''' was an attempt to bring the [[Summer Olympic Games]] to the city of [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] in 2024; the games were ultimately awarded to the city for 2028. Following withdrawals by other bidding cities during the [[2024 Summer Olympics]] bidding process that led to just two candidate cities (Los Angeles and [[Paris bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics|Paris]]), the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) announced that the [[2028 Summer Olympics]] would be awarded at the same time as 2024. After extended negotiations, Los Angeles agreed to bid for the 2028 Games if certain conditions were met. On July 31, 2017, the IOC announced Los Angeles as the sole candidate for the 2028 games, with [[US Dollar|$]]1.8 billion of additional funding to support local sports and the Games program.\n\nLos Angeles was chosen by the [[United States Olympic Committee]] (USOC) on August 28, 2015, after the [[Los Angeles City Council]] voted unanimously to back the bid. Los Angeles was the second city submitted by the USOC for the 2024 Summer Olympics. [[Boston bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics|Boston]] was originally chosen to be the American bid but withdrew on July 27, 2015. Los Angeles also originally bid for the USOC's nomination in late 2014, when Boston was chosen over Los Angeles, [[Washington, D.C.]], and [[San Francisco]]. This was the third United States summer bid since hosting the [[Centennial Olympic Games]] (1996) in Atlanta, previously losing in 2012 and 2016 to London and Rio de Janeiro.\n\nLos Angeles previously hosted the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] and the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] and will become the third city \u2013 after London and Paris in 2024 \u2013 to host the Summer Games three times. Los Angeles will become the first American city to host the Olympic games since the [[2002 Winter Olympics]] in [[Salt Lake City]]. It will be the fifth time a US city has hosted the Summer Olympics.\n\n==Bid history==\n\n[[File:LA2024 FinalLogo.png|thumb|left|Initial campaign logo]]\nIn 2006, [[Los Angeles bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics|Los Angeles entered the bidding]] to become the US applicant city for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]]; the [[United States Olympic Committee]] (USOC) selected [[Chicago bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics|Chicago]] instead that year. In September 2011, Los Angeles was awarded the [[2015 Special Olympics World Summer Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.specialolympics.org/los-angeles-2015.aspx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111025937/http://specialolympics.org/los-angeles-2015.aspx |archivedate=November 11, 2011 |title=Los Angeles 2015 |publisher=Special Olympics |date=September 14, 2011 |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In March 2013, Mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] sent a letter to the USOC stating that the city was interested in bidding to host the 2024 Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/07/olympics-2024-los-angeles_n_2831607.html|title=2024 Olympic Games?|date=March 7, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204033611/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/07/olympics-2024-los-angeles_n_2831607.html|archivedate=December 4, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On September 17, 2013, the LA County Board of Supervisors unanimously approved a resolution seeking interest in the games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2013/09/17/los-angeles-board-formally-states-interest-in-hosting-2024-olympics/ |title=Los Angeles Board Formally States Interest In Hosting 2024 Olympics |publisher=CBS Los Angeles |accessdate=September 17, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111041747/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2013/09/17/los-angeles-board-formally-states-interest-in-hosting-2024-olympics/ |archivedate=November 11, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 2014, the Southern California Committee for the Olympic Games announced its bid proposal for the 2024 Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sccog.org/ |title=Southern California Committee for the Olympic Games |work=sccog.org |year=2014 |accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref>  On 28 July 2015, the USOC contacted Los Angeles about stepping in as a replacement bidder for the 2024 Summer Games after Boston dropped its bid.<ref name=\"USOC Contacts LA\">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-usoc-contacts-los-angeles-20150728-story.html | title=U.S. Olympic Committee contacts Los Angeles about 2024 Summer Games | date=28 July 2015 | accessdate=30 July 2015 | author=Wharton, David}}</ref> On 1 September 2015, the LA City Council voted 15\u20130 to support a bid for the 2024 Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abc7.com/sports/la-city-council-unanimously-in-favor-of-2024-olympic-bid/965189/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925132231/http://abc7.com/sports/la-city-council-unanimously-in-favor-of-2024-olympic-bid/965189/|archivedate=25 September 2015 |title=USOC endorses Los Angeles for 2024 Olympics bid |publisher=[[KABC-TV|ABC 7 Los Angeles]] |date=1 September 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref> The U.S. Olympic Committee finalised its selection moments after the LA City Council's vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/more/la-sp-sn-usoc-los-angeles-2024-summer-olympics-20150901-story.html |title=USOC names Los Angeles the official U.S. bidder for the 2024 Summer Olympics |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=1 September 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://abc7.com/sports/garcetti-travels-abroad-to-present-las-2024-olympic-bid-to-ioc/966776/ |title=Angelenos have mixed opinions about 2024 Olympic bid |publisher=[[KABC-TV|ABC 7 Los Angeles]] |date=2 September 2015 |accessdate=11 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 13 January 2016, Los Angeles 2024 committee officials said they were \"thrilled to welcome\" the construction of a $2-billion-plus, [[SoFi Stadium|state-of-the-art football stadium]] in [[Inglewood, California]] and believed the arrival of [[Los Angeles Rams|one]]\u2014and perhaps [[Los Angeles Chargers|two]]\u2014[[National Football League|NFL]] teams would bolster its chances.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-nfl-olympic-bid-20160113-story.html |title=NFL stadium could boost L.A.'s Olympic bid |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 2016 |accessdate=13 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115013152/http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-nfl-olympic-bid-20160113-story.html |archivedate=15 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 25 January 2016, the Los Angeles 2024 committee announced that it planned to place its [[Olympic Village]] on the [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] campus. LA 2024 also announced that media members and some Olympic officials would be housed in a 15-acre residential complex [[University of Southern California|USC]] planned to build.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-ucla-2024-olympics-20160125-story.html |title=Where would L.A. put all those Olympic athletes? Panel looks at UCLA |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 2016 |accessdate=25 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125232042/http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-ucla-2024-olympics-20160125-story.html |archivedate=25 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February 2016, LA 2024 unveiled a new logo and its slogan, \"Follow the sun.\"<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-la-2024-olympic-logo-20160216-story.html |title= LA 2024 unveils logo for Olympic bid|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=February 2016| accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> On 23 February 2016, more than 88% of Angelenos were in favor of the city's hosting the 2024 Olympic and Paralympic Games bid, according to a survey conducted by [[Loyola Marymount University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/more/la-sp-la-2024-olympic-bid-public-support-poll-20160223-story.html|title= LA 2024 Olympic bid receives wide public support in new poll|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=February 2016| accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref> On 10 March 2016, Los Angeles officials bidding for the 2024 Summer Olympics turned their focus to temporary facilities that might be needed. Current plans include an elevated track built over the football field at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] and a proposal to temporarily convert [[Figueroa Street]] into a miles-long promenade for pedestrians and bicyclists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la-2024-olympics-20160311-story.html |title=LA 2024 mulls temporary Olympic facilities&nbsp;\u2013 a raised Coliseum track, maybe? |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 2016 |accessdate=10 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311103544/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la-2024-olympics-20160311-story.html |archivedate=11 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June 2016, the IOC confirmed that Los Angeles would proceed to the second stage of bidding for the 2024 Summer Games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-sn-2024-olympic-bid-stage-two-20160602-snap-story.html|title=L.A. advances to next stage of 2024 Olympic bidding process|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=June 2016|accessdate=2 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602220621/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-sn-2024-olympic-bid-stage-two-20160602-snap-story.html|archivedate=2 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 29 July 2016, LA 2024 officials released artist renderings of an updated [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] and [[Dedeaux Field|temporary swim stadium]] that would be used if Los Angeles is awarded the 2024 Summer Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-releases-renderings-of-updated-1469826459-htmlstory.html|title=LA 2024 releases renderings of updated Coliseum, temporary swim stadium|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801042047/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-releases-renderings-of-updated-1469826459-htmlstory.html|archivedate=1 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2016, [[Mayor of Los Angeles|Mayor]] [[Eric Garcetti]] led a 25-person contingent from Los Angeles to [[Rio de Janeiro]] to promote their city's bid for the 2024 Summer Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-brings-large-crew-to-rio-1469996962-htmlstory.html|title=LA 2024 brings large crew to Rio Olympics|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 2016|accessdate=31 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731231145/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-oly-rio-2016-la-2024-brings-large-crew-to-rio-1469996962-htmlstory.html|archivedate=31 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 7 September 2016, LA 2024 planned to send a 16-person delegation to the [[2016 Paralympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] as part of its ongoing campaign to bring the Olympics back to Southern California.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la-2024-paralympics-20160907-snap-story.html|title=LA 2024 will send a delegation of 16 people to 2016 Paralympics in Rio||publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 2016|  accessdate =7 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September 2016, the LA 2024 bid committee released a two-minute video featuring a montage of local scenes narrated by children talking about their \"dream city\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-la2024-video-20160913-snap-story.html|title=LA 2024 video marks one year until Olympic leaders select host for 2024 Summer Games|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 2016|accessdate=13 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914112054/http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-la2024-video-20160913-snap-story.html|archivedate=14 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 23 September 2016, LA 2024 agreed to terms with the [[U.S. Olympic Committee]] on a required but controversial marketing arrangement. The Joint Marketing Program Agreement outlines shared responsibilities\u2014and shared income\u2014between Los Angeles and the USOC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-joint-marketing-20160923-snap-story.html|title=LA 2024 and U.S. Olympic leaders come to terms on marketing agreement|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924014857/http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-joint-marketing-20160923-snap-story.html|archivedate=24 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 7 October 2016, LA 2024 officials again made adjustments to their proposal for the 2024 Summer Olympics, moving half of a large and potentially expensive media center to the [[University of Southern California|USC]] campus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/la-sp-sn-la2024-second-filing-20161007-snap-story.html|title=LA 2024 relocates Summer Olympics press center to USC in latest bid documents|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 2016|accessdate=7 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008171201/http://www.latimes.com/la-sp-sn-la2024-second-filing-20161007-snap-story.html|archivedate=8 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 21 October 2016, the LA 2024 bid committee again enlisted U.S. Olympians to help make the case for bringing the Summer Olympics back to Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-sn-la2024-video-20161021-snap-story.html|title=U.S. Olympians make video pitches for Los Angeles' 2024 bid|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 2016|accessdate=21 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022092645/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-sn-la2024-video-20161021-snap-story.html|archivedate=22 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2016, LA 2024 issued a statement noting \"LA 2024 congratulates President-elect [[Donald Trump|Donald J. Trump]] and appreciates his longstanding support of the Olympic movement in the United States. We strongly believe the Olympics and LA 2024 transcend politics and can help unify our diverse communities and our world.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-trump-olympics-la2024-20161109-story.html|title=LA 2024 is about to find out how a Donald Trump presidency will affect Los Angeles' Olympic bid|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 2016|accessdate=9 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109234228/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-trump-olympics-la2024-20161109-story.html|archivedate=9 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 12 November 2016, Mayor [[Eric Garcetti]] and six-time gold medalist sprinter [[Allyson Felix]] led an LA 2024 presentation to an array of Olympic leaders and sports officials at a general assembly for the Assn. of [[National Olympic Committees]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/15/2024-olympics-la/|title=LA Committee Lobbies For 2024 Olympics In Qatar|access-date=2017-05-18|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223135831/http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2016/11/15/2024-olympics-la/|archivedate=23 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 23 November 2016, [[President-elect]] Trump expressed his support for Los Angeles's 2024 Olympic bid during a phone call with Mayor [[Eric Garcetti|Garcetti]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-trump-garcetti-phone-20161123-story.html|title=Trump supports L.A.'s Olympic bid, Mayor Garcetti's office says|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 2016|accessdate=24 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161124052306/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-ln-trump-garcetti-phone-20161123-story.html|archivedate=24 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 2 December 2016, LA 2024 released a new budget estimating it would spend $5.3 billion to stage the Games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-olympics-la-2024-story.html|title=LA 2024 releases revised budget for Olympics, revenue to equal $5.3 billion in costs|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 2016|accessdate=2 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202233955/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-olympics-la-2024-story.html|archivedate=2 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 January 2017, Angeleno Olympians and Paralympians rode on the [[Rose Parade]] float titled \"Follow the Sun\" to promote the city's bid.<ref>{{cite press release |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Top Olympians and Paralympians to Ride the City of Los Angeles and LA 2024 \u201cFollow the Sun\u201d Float in 128th Rose Parade |url= https://la24.org/media/1118-rose-parade-float |agency= LA 2024 |date= 2016-11-18 |access-date= 2017-01-24 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170202013448/https://la24.org/media/1118-rose-parade-float |archivedate= February 2, 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> On 9 January 2017, LA 2024 issued a report predicting that the mega-sporting event would boost the local economy by $11.2 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-sn-oly-econ-impact-20170109-story.html|title=L.A. Olympic bid report forecasts $11-billion impact on local economy|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 2017|accessdate=9 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110015929/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-sn-oly-econ-impact-20170109-story.html|archivedate=10 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 25 January 2017, the [[Los Angeles City Council]] gave unanimous final approval for a privately run bid.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la-2024-contract-20170125-story.html|title=City Council unanimous in final approval for L.A. to host 2024 Olympics|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 2017|accessdate=25 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125202345/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la-2024-contract-20170125-story.html|archivedate=25 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 28 February 2017, it was announced that four [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] [[film studio]]s ([[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[20th Century Fox|Fox]], [[NBCUniversal]], and [[Warner Bros]]) would be helping promote the Los Angeles bid.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-olympics-studios-20170228-story.html|title=Hollywood studios help L.A. with 2024 Olympics bid|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 2017|accessdate=28 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301012905/http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-olympics-studios-20170228-story.html|archivedate=1 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 20 April 2017, the private committee trying to bring the Summer Olympics back to Los Angeles has issued a new set of renderings and videos showing what those Games might look like.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la24-renderings-20170420-story.html|title=LA 2024 releases new visuals of potential Olympic Games|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 2017|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421093623/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la24-renderings-20170420-story.html|archivedate=21 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the decision to award the 2024 and 2028 games simultaneously, Los Angeles announced that it would consider a bid for the 2028 Games if certain conditions were met.<ref name=\"LA May\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2017/05/13/la-may-consider-2028-olympics-if-2024-bid-falls-through/|title=LA may consider 2028 Olympics if 2024 bid falls through|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2017-05-13|website=New York Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517044743/http://nypost.com/2017/05/13/la-may-consider-2028-olympics-if-2024-bid-falls-through/|archivedate=17 May 2017|access-date=2017-05-18|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 31 July 2017, the IOC announced Los Angeles as the sole candidate for the 2028 games, with [[US Dollar|$]]1.8 billion of additional funding to support local sport and the Games program.<ref name=\"LA 2028\">{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/los-angeles-declares-candidature-for-olympic-games-2028-ioc-to-contribute-usd-1-8-billion-to-the-local-organising-committee|title=Los Angeles Declares Candidature for Oylmpic Games 2028 - IOC to Contribute USD 1.8Billion to the Local Organizing Committee|publisher=IOC|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> On August 29, 2018, Olympic officials arrived for a two-day visit that included meetings with local organizers and a tour of the city's newest venues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la28-ioc-20180828-story.html|title=Olympic officials visit L.A. for the first time since awarding the bid and are impressed so far with what's to come|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 2018| accessdate =29 August 2018}}</ref> On April 17, 2019, LA2028 announced that it would partner with [[NBC Universal]] to sell media, sponsorship deals in tandem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-los-angeles-2028-olympics-sponsorships-20190416-story.html|title=L.A. 2028 Olympics officials hope new sponsorship strategy results in revenue boost|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 2019| accessdate =17 April 2019}}</ref> On April 25, 2019, LA2028 expanded its staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-la2028-expands-staff-20190425-story.html|title=LA 2028 Olympic organizing committee staff gets some fresh faces|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 2019| accessdate =29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bid process==\n{{Main|2024 Summer Olympics}}\n\n===IOC===\n\n'''2024 Olympic Bid Evaluation Commission''':<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamesbids.com/eng/summer-olympic-bids/namibias-fredericks-to-chair-2024-olympic-bid-evaluation-commission/|title=2024 Olympics Bid Evaluation Commission|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013173513/http://gamesbids.com/eng/summer-olympic-bids/namibias-fredericks-to-chair-2024-olympic-bid-evaluation-commission/|archivedate=October 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Patrick Baumann (basketball)|Patrick Baumann]]: Chair<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mr-patrick-baumann|title=Patrick Baumann|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807030540/https://www.olympic.org/mr-patrick-baumann|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n* Marisol Casado: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mrs-marisol-casado|title=Marisol Casado|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807030748/https://www.olympic.org/mrs-marisol-casado|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n* [[Mikee Cojuangco-Jaworski|Mikaela Cojuangco Jaworski]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mrs-mikaela-cojuangco-jaworski|title=Mikaela Cojuangco Jaworski|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807030927/https://www.olympic.org/mrs-mikaela-cojuangco-jaworski|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Kirsty Coventry]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/ms-kirsty-coventry|title=Kirsty Coventry|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807030940/https://www.olympic.org/ms-kirsty-coventry|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n* [[Nawal El Moutawakel]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/ms-nawal-el-moutawakel|title=Nawal El Moutawakel|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807031503/https://www.olympic.org/ms-nawal-el-moutawakel|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Ugur Erdener]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/dr-ugur-erdener|title=Ugur Erdener|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807031523/https://www.olympic.org/dr-ugur-erdener|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n* Habu Gumel: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mr-habu-gumel|title=Habu Gumel|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807031732/https://www.olympic.org/mr-habu-gumel|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Poul-Erik Hoyer]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mr-poul-erik-hoyer|title=Poul-Erik H\u00f8yer|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807031845/https://www.olympic.org/mr-poul-erik-hoyer|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Duane Kale]]: Member\n* [[Gunilla Lindberg]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mrs-gunilla-lindberg|title=Gunilla Lindberg|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815031054/https://www.olympic.org/mrs-gunilla-lindberg|archivedate=August 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Bernard Rajzman]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mr-bernard-rajzman|title=Bernard Rajzman|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807032806/https://www.olympic.org/mr-bernard-rajzman|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Kereyn Smith: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olympic.org.nz/athletes/kereyn-smith/|title=Kereyn Smith}}</ref> \n* [[Tsunekazu Takeda]]: Member<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/mr-tsunekazu-takeda|title=Tsunekazu Takeda|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807033033/https://www.olympic.org/mr-tsunekazu-takeda|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Budget==\n\n===Revenues===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Revenue description<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n!OCOG revenue<br> ($ million in 2024)\n!% of revenue\n|-\n|IOC contribution\n|align=right|$898.0\n|align=right|13.8%\n|-\n|Broadcast of TOP sponsorships\n|align=right|$437\n|align=right|7.3%\n|-\n|Domestic sponsorships\n|align=right|$2517.7\n|align=right|36.3%\n|-\n|Sports ticketing revenue\n|align=right|$1928.8\n|align=right|28.9%\n|-\n|Licensing and merchandise\n|align=right|$304.9\n|align=right|4.2%\n|-\n|Government contribution or grants\n|align=right|$11.6\n|align=right|0.2%\n|-\n|Lotteries and licensing royalties<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n|align=right|$8.1\n|align=right|0.1%\n|-\n|Other revenues\n|align=right|$570.9\n|align=right|9.2%\n|-\n|'''Total revenues'''\n|align=right|'''$6,884.2'''\n|align=right|'''100%'''\n|}\n\nUCLA, [[University of Southern California]] (USC), NBC Universal, [[Los Angeles Rams]] and the City of Los Angeles are currently modernizing or building infrastructure for future Olympic venues totaling over $3 billion. Not listed as non-OCOG (Organizing Committee for Olympic Games).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://olympics.nbcsports.com/2017/02/03/la-2024-olympic-bid-book-venues-ticket-prices/|title=Los Angeles 2024 Olympic projected ticket prices, venue map in bid book|publisher=NBC Sports|agency=Associated Press|date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208035239/http://olympics.nbcsports.com/2017/02/03/la-2024-olympic-bid-book-venues-ticket-prices/|archivedate=February 8, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Los Angeles has guaranteed to sign the required Olympic City Charter and be the sole entity responsible for the games and any cost surplus or overruns. The City has pledged to contribute $250 million to cover any cost overruns. The State of California has created an Olympic Games Trust Fund that would pay for potential budget overruns up to $250 million. Both government guaranty payments would take place only if LA 2024's private insurance proves inadequate to cover cost overruns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/events/20160930/los-angeles-city-council-approves-stage-ii-documents-for-2024-olympic-games|first1=Scott M.|last1=Reid|title=Los Angeles City Council approves Stage II documents for 2024 Olympic Games|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230002315/http://www.dailynews.com/events/20160930/los-angeles-city-council-approves-stage-ii-documents-for-2024-olympic-games|archivedate=December 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe theme and bid embodies Agenda 2020 reforms of Olympics in Los Angeles, a surplus of $161 million is predicted. On January 9, 2017, the LA 2024 committee issued a report predicting that the Olympics would boost the local economy by $11.2 billion.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-sn-oly-econ-impact-20170109-story.html|title=L.A. Olympic bid report forecasts $11-billion impact on local economy|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 2017|accessdate=January 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110015929/http://www.latimes.com/sports/olympics/la-sp-sn-oly-econ-impact-20170109-story.html|archivedate=January 10, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-la-2028-olympics-budget-20190429-story.html|title=Estimated cost of 2028 Los Angeles Olympics jumps to $6.9 billion|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 2019| accessdate =30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation and infrastructure==\n{{Main|Transportation in Los Angeles}}\n\n[[LAX]], the city's main airport, is investing more than US$1.9 billion into an expansion of the Tom Bradley International Terminal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lamayor.org/mayor-garcetti-breaks-ground-new-16-billion-lax-terminal|title=MAYOR GARCETTI BREAKS GROUND ON NEW $1.6 BILLION LAX TERMINAL|publisher=LA Mayor|date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228164240/https://www.lamayor.org/mayor-garcetti-breaks-ground-new-16-billion-lax-terminal|archivedate=February 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The new Midfield Concourse Terminal is scheduled to add 11 gates for 2019, and many other improvements are planned with an expected completion date of 2023.<ref name=\"la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com\">{{cite web|title=Stage 1 Vision, Games Concept and Strategy|url=https://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part1_english.pdf|accessdate=July 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012093258/http://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part1_english.pdf|archivedate=October 12, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Los Angeles Metro Rail|Los Angeles Metro]] passed a [[Measure R|county-wide measure]] expanding the county of Los Angeles' transportation tax for modernization of its infrastructure in 2008. This measure provides funding for many of the highest priority projects, including the [[Crenshaw/LAX Line]] connecting to LAX, [[Regional Connector]] light rail subway line corridor thru Downtown LA to Santa Monica and Long Beach, [[Purple Line Extension]] [[Rapid Transit|subway]] to UCLA, the [[Los Angeles Streetcar]] through downtown LA and five other transit lines and projects in the draft stages. The Purple Line and Crenshaw/LAX connectors are to be completed in time for 2024. The transportation plans are already fully funded by LA County voters. A second measure, Measure M, which passed in November 2016 elections, will extend the transportation tax funds indefinitely and speed many other projects with $120 billion in highway and transit projects over forty years, including a [[Sepulveda Pass Transit Corridor|Sepulveda Subway line from the Valley]] to the Los Angeles westside thru the [[Sepulveda Pass]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.net/projects/sfv-405/|title=Sepulveda Pass Corridor|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806003057/http://www.metro.net/projects/sfv-405/|archivedate=August 6, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nLA 2024 bid leaders are touting these measures and infrastructure improvements as indicators of the new Los Angeles and a car-free Olympics in a city known for its car culture.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} 158.5&nbsp;km (98 miles) of new rails, 93 stations and 350,000 daily average boardings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.net/news/facts-glance/|title=Facts at a Glance|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106091341/http://www.metro.net/news/facts-glance/|archivedate=November 6, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Los Angeles had no rail lines in 1984. Bid leaders indicate public rail transportation lines will be available to all of the clusters: [[Downtown Long Beach station|Downtown Long Beach]], [[Balboa station|San Fernando Valley Sports Park]], [[7th Street/Metro Center station|Downtown L.A.]], and the [[Expo Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Santa Monica beach cluster]].<ref>{{cite report |date=December 2003 |title=Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority: It Is Too Early to Predict Service Sector Success, but Opportunities for Improved Analysis and Communication Exist |url=http://www.bsa.ca.gov/pdfs/reports/2002-116.pdf |publisher=[[California State Auditor]] |accessdate=September 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221004418/http://www.bsa.ca.gov/pdfs/reports/2002-116.pdf |archivedate=December 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==LA 2024 Bid Committee==\n<!--Leave formatted as is; this is the official title and should be capitalized-->\n* [[Jerry Brown]]: [[Governor of California]]\n\n===Leadership===\n* [[Eric Garcetti]]: [[Mayor of Los Angeles]]\n* [[Casey Wasserman]]: Chair, LA 2024\n* [[Gene Sykes]]: Chief Executive Officer\n* [[Maria Elena Durazo]]: Vice Chair\n* [[Earvin \"Magic\" Johnson]]: Vice Chair\n* [[Janet Evans]]: Vice Chair, Director, Athlete Relations\n* [[Larry Probst]]: Chairman USOC\n* [[Anita Defrantz]]: US IOC Member, Senior Advisor for Legacy\n* [[Angela Ruggiero]]: US IOC Member\n* [[Terrance Burns]]: Chief Marketing Officer\n* [[John Harper (Consultant)|John Harper]]: Chief Operations Officer\n* [[Jeff Millman]]: Chief Communications Officer\n* [[Brence Culp]]: Executive Director, Housing\n* [[Carla Garcia (Consultant)|Carla Garcia]]: Director, Administrative Operations\n* Brian Nelson: General Counsel\n* [[Peter Tomozawa]]: Executive Director, Partnerships and Board Relations\n* [[Tanja Olando]]: Deputy General Counsel\n* [[Lenny Abbey]]: Director NOC/NPC Relations and Operations\n* [[Jared Schott]]: Director of International Relations and Assistant General Counsel\n\nIn addition, the 2024 Bid Committee includes a 108-member athletes' advisory committee, which includes [[Andre Agassi]], [[Allyson Felix]], [[Michelle Kwan]], [[Katie Ledecky]], [[Greg Louganis]], [[Carl Lewis]], [[Apolo Ohno]], [[Landon Donovan]], [[Kobe Bryant]] and [[Michael Phelps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://la24.org/leadership|title=Leadership|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819105923/https://la24.org/leadership|archivedate=August 19, 2016|df=mdy-all|access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy of the Games==\n\n===Sport legacy===\nThe Los Angeles Olympic bid committee has stated that its legacy will be delivering a sustainable model for the bidding process and delivery of a cost-effective Olympic Games.<ref name=\"la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com\"/> Los Angeles bid leaders are focusing on delivering an Olympic Games for the best athlete experience and not a centerpiece for a city revitalization project, as was recently the case for [[2014 Winter Olympics|Sochi, Russia]] and [[2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing, China]]. Bid leaders have indicated Los Angeles is transforming itself, does not need a city showcase, and has the ability to showcase the athletes instead.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Social and economic benefit==\nThe theme and bid embodies the Agenda 2020 reforms of Olympics in Los Angeles, a surplus of $161 million is predicted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/olympics/2015/08/25/los-angeles-projects-161-million-surplus--olympics/32359841/|title=Los Angeles projects $161 million surplus for 2024 Olympic Games|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> On January 9, 2017, the LA 2024 committee made a report saying that the Olympics would boost the local economy by $11.2 billion.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/>\n\n==Proposed venues==\nThe 2024 Los Angeles Olympic bid uses existing venues, venues under construction and new temporary venues in and around the City of Los Angeles.<ref name=\"la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com\"/> Approximately half of the venues are outside the City of Los Angeles.\n\nMany of the proposed venues are facilities constructed after the 1984 games. Staples Center opened in 1999. Stub Hub Center was opened in 2003. Galen Center was opened in 2006. Microsoft Theater opened in 2007.  UCLA proposed the Olympic Village on their campus with dorms built-in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/ucla-selected-as-site-of-olympic-village-for-2024-bid|title=UCLA selected as site of Olympic Village for 2024 bid|first=UCLA|last=Newsroom|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814094340/http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/ucla-selected-as-site-of-olympic-village-for-2024-bid|archivedate=August 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rose Bowl was renovated in 2013. The Forum was recently renovated in 2014. USC \"University Village\" opened in 2017. The \"MyFigueroa\" street redevelopment project is currently under construction. Banc of California Soccer Stadium and the American Football L.A. Stadium at Hollywood Park are currently under construction with completion dates of 2018 and 2020 respectively. The Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum renovations are scheduled to begin in mid-2017 by USC. The Los Angeles Convention Center (LACOEX) remodel and additions are to begin in 2018. The NBC/IBC proposed center is set to be completed in 2019. All of these proposed venues will be renovated or completed with or without the Olympic Games being awarded.\n\n===Downtown Los Angeles Sports Park===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Events\n!Capacity\n!Status\n|-\n|[[Figueroa Street]]<ref name=\"la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com\" />\n|Live site: \"Olympic Way\"\n|N/A\n|Existing\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]\n|Athletics\n| rowspan=\"2\" |70,000\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Existing\n|-\n|Closing Ceremonies\n|-\n|[[Dodger Stadium]]\n|Baseball and softball (preliminaries, finals)\n|56,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|[[Banc of California Stadium]]\n|Football (preliminaries)\n|22,000\n|Under construction\n|-\n|[[Dedeaux Field]] (USC)\n|Swimming, diving, synchronized swimming\n|20,000\n|Existing\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Galen Center]] (USC)\n|Badminton\n| rowspan=\"2\" |10,300\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Existing\n|-\n|Karate\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[Los Angeles Convention Center]]\n|Basketball (women's preliminaries)\n|8,000\n| rowspan=\"6\" |Existing\n|-\n|Boxing \n|8,000\n|-\n|Fencing\n|\n|-\n|Taekwondo \n|7,000\n|-\n|Table tennis\n|5,000\n|-\n|BMX freestyle\n|\n|-\n|[[Staples Center]]\n|Basketball (preliminaries, finals)\n|18,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|[[Microsoft Theater]]\n|Weightlifting \n|7,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|[[University of Southern California#University Village|University Village]] (USC)\n|Media Village\n|N/A\n|Existing\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Los Angeles City Hall|City Hall]]\n|Marathon\n| rowspan=\"3\" |5,000\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Existing\n|-\n|Race walk\n|-\n|Road cycling\n|}\n\n===Valley Sports Park===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Events\n!Capacity\n!Status\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" |[[Sepulveda Dam#Sepulveda Basin Recreational Area|Sepulveda Basin Park]], Los Angeles, CA\n|Canoe slalom\n|8,000\n|Planned construction\n|-\n|Equestrian\n|15,000\n|Temporary structure\n|-\n|Shooting\n|3,000\n|Temporary structure\n|}\n\n===South Bay Sports Park===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Events\n!Capacity\n!Status\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\" |[[StubHub Center]], Carson, CA\n|Rugby\n|30,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Modern pentathlon \n|30,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Tennis\n|10,000 (center court)\n|Existing\n|-\n|Field hockey\n|15,000 (primary field; secondary field 5,000)\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[VELO Sports Center]], Carson, CA\n|Track cycling\n|6,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Modern pentathlon fencing\n|6,000\n|Existing\n|}\n\n===Long Beach Sports Park===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Events\n!Capacity\n!Status\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Downtown Long Beach|Long Beach Waterfront]], Long Beach, CA\n|BMX cycling\n|6,000\n|Temporary\n|-\n|Water polo\n|8,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Triathlon\n|2,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Open water swimming\n|2,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Long Beach Arena]], Long Beach, CA\n|Handball\n|12,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Long Beach Convention Center]], Long Beach, CA\n|Sports climbing\n|10,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Belmont Veterans Memorial Pier]], Long Beach, CA\n|Sailing\n|6,000\n|Existing\n|}\n\n===Other Venues===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Events\n!Capacity\n!Status\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Rose Bowl, Pasadena]], CA\n|Football\n|92,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Angel Stadium]], Anaheim, CA\n|Baseball and softball\n|45,457\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Lake Perris]], Moreno Valley,CA / Perris,CA\n|Canoe sprint\n|12,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Rowing\n|12,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Frank G. Bonelli Regional Park]], San Dimas, CA\n|Mountain biking\n|3,000\n|Temporary\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Honda Center]], Anaheim, CA\n|Indoor volleyball\n|18,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Universal Studios Hollywood|Universal Studios]], Hollywood, CA\n|[[International Broadcast Centre|International Broadcast Center]]/MPC<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/biz/news/universal-studios-hollywood-soundstage-theme-park-expansion-1201795566/|title=Universal to Build New Soundstage Complex, Expand Theme Park in 5-Year Plan (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Ted|last=Johnson|date=June 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827100145/http://variety.com/2016/biz/news/universal-studios-hollywood-soundstage-theme-park-expansion-1201795566/|archivedate=August 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| \u2013\n|Existing\n|-\n!\n![[Westside (Los Angeles County)|Los Angeles Westside Area]]\n!\n!\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Santa Monica State Beach]], Santa Monica, CA\n|Beach volleyball\n|12,000\n|Temporary\n|-\n|Skateboarding\n|10,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|Surfing\n|8,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|3&times;3 Basketball\n| \u2013\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Riviera Country Club]], Los Angeles, CA\n|Golf\n|30,000\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Pauley Pavilion]] ([[UCLA]]), Westwood, CA\n|Olympic Village, Olympic Village Training Center\n| \u2013\n|Existing\n|-\n|Wrestling\n|12,500\n|Existing\n|-\n|Judo\n|12,500\n|Existing\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[SoFi Stadium|LA Stadium at Hollywood Park]], Inglewood, CA\n|Opening and Closing Ceremonies\n|100,000\n|Under construction\n|-\n|Football\n|100,000\n|Under construction\n|-\n|Archery \n|8,000 (Stadium Lake)\n|Under construction\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]], Inglewood, CA\n|Gymnastics\n|17,000\n|Existing\n|}\n\n====Olympic ceremonies====\nOlympic ceremonies could be held in two venues simultaneously; the ceremony would begin at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] in Exposition Park to honor the legacy of the Olympics in Los Angeles and then transfer to the new [[SoFi Stadium]] in Inglewood to proceed with the parade of athletes, oaths, traditional Olympic protocol and the lighting of a cauldron. LA 2024 bid leaders wish to use the new LA stadium to dispel negative thought about using the LA Memorial Coliseum for a third Olympics. They also cite ticket sales at both sites as extra cash flow for the committee. The LA 2024 team also stated they would reverse the closing ceremony with a start at LA Stadium and close the show at the LA Coliseum if chosen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-la2024-olympic-ceremonies-20170116-story.html|title=L.A. organizers propose linked, simultaneous Olympic ceremonies for Coliseum, Inglewood stadium|date=January 16, 2017|publisher=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116175332/http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-la2024-olympic-ceremonies-20170116-story.html|archivedate=January 16, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Football (soccer) stadia==\nFootball venues will be situated within [[Los Angeles]] and in other parts of California, to be determined.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part3_english.pdf|title=LA2024 Games Delivery, Experience and Venue Legacy|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204004759/https://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part3_english.pdf|archivedate=February 4, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nPotential venues:\n* [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]], [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] (92,542 capacity) \u2013 3 group matches, quarterfinals, semifinals and women's final\n* [[SoFi Stadium]], [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]] (80,000) \u2013 3 group matches, quarterfinals, semifinals and men's final\n* [[Levi's Stadium]], [[Santa Clara, California]] (68,500) \u2013 5 group matches, quarterfinals, and men's bronze medal match\n* [[California Memorial Stadium]], [[Berkeley, California]] (63,000) - 8 group matches\n* [[Stanford Stadium]], [[Stanford, California|Stanford]] (50,000) \u2013 5 group matches, quarterfinals and women's bronze medal match\n* New [[MLS]] Stadium, [[San Diego]] (32,000) \u2013 8 group matches\n* [[Banc of California Stadium]], [[Exposition Park, Los Angeles|Exposition Park]] (22,000) \u2013 8 group matches\n* [[Avaya Stadium]], [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] (20,000) \u2013 8 group matches\n\nAccording to LA2024.org there will be eight venues in the borders of State of California (probably eight venues in four municipalities).\n\n===Changed venues===\nPiggyback Yard, a rail yard along the [[LA River]], was the original proposed location for the Olympic Village. The plan was abandoned due to financial concerns and UCLA was chosen as the new proposed location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://la.curbed.com/2016/1/25/10843466/los-angeles-2024-olympics-village-piggyback-yard-ucla-usc|title=Los Angeles Abandons Plans to Rehabilitate Prime LA River Site For 2024 Olympics|first=Adrian Glick|last=Kudler|date=January 25, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160813093652/http://la.curbed.com/2016/1/25/10843466/los-angeles-2024-olympics-village-piggyback-yard-ucla-usc|archivedate=August 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1932 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[1984 Summer Olympics]]\n* [[Los Angeles bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160422105136/https://la24.org/ LA 2024]\n* [https://twitter.com/LA2024 LA 2024 on Twitter]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/la2024 LA 2024 on Facebook]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/LA2028Games/ LA 2024 on Instagram]\n\n===Candidature documents===\n* [http://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditature-part1_english.pdf Stage 1: Vision, Games Concept and Strategy]\n* [http://la24-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/pdf/LA2024-canditatur